Expansion and dilemma of Intensive Care Unit

By Danni Peng

PUBLISHED: June 3,2019

Pushing open the closed door of the ICU ward of the First People's Hospital in Shangqiu City, Henan Province, we could see that most of the patients on the beds were with their eyes closed. Some of them were in a comatose state, some were injected with sedatives, and occasionally some were awake, and you don't have a look on your face. Here, social status, identity and gender lose their meaning -- as if dozens of patients don't wear clothes or eat at all, patients are sheared off in the middle, covered in tubes and fed by feeding tubes. Day and night running equipment and never-extinguished lights, so that this closed space without the concept of day and night. To prevent delirium or restlessness, many patients'hands and feet were strapped to the edge of the bed.

The ICU at the hospital, which had 13 beds when it was founded 10 years ago, has grown to 20. To cope with the increasing patient demand, the 28-bed second ward will be put into operation soon. In addition, movable beds are readily available to allow for additional beds when there are insufficient beds. During the peak period, a total of 80 patients are expected to be admitted to the two wards.

One patient groaned and said fitfully, "I want to go home, " to no one's attention. According to the guidelines of the former Ministry of Health (see below) , one ICU bed should be staffed by three nurses; in this case, however, one nurse is responsible for three beds. Various Examinations; drug supplementation; regular recording of heart rate and blood pressure on the Monitor; cleaning of patients'stool and urine, and turning patients over at set times to prevent bedsores on their backs... These jobs have overwhelmed nurses during 12 hour shifts, leaving them with little time for the mental health or even the dignity of their caregivers. "It's like a wet market in high season, " said one nurse.

But none of this stopped the rapid expansion of the ICU.

Rapid expansion

The ICU hasn't always been this hot. In 2009, when Liu Xiaojun became director of the Intensive Care Unit of the Second Affiliated Hospital of Zhengzhou University, he found that the ICU had only eight beds in its three-year history, but it was still "hungry" . By contrast, the ICU at the First Affiliated Hospital of Zhengzhou University in Florida, less than 5 km away, is chronically overcrowded with hundreds of beds. Had it not been for the state's mandatory requirement for ICU wards in level-iii hospitals, the ICU in Zheng's second affiliated hospital might have closed down. There are few patients, no bonuses, no room for growth and a lack of morale. "You've come to the wrong place, " colleagues told Liu

ICU, or intensive care unit, is a specialized ward for intensive care and treatment in hospitals. It dates back to the early days of the 1950s. At the time, polio caused many deaths from respiratory failure in Copenhagen, Denmark. The medical staff responsible for the care found that the death rate dropped from 87% to 40% after the patient was centrally managed, tracheotomy and cardiopulmonary resuscitation.

More than 30 years after Denmark created the world's first ICU ward, China's first ICU bed for surgery was built at Peking Union Medical College Hospital in 1982. Two years later, Concorde set up China's First Department of Critical Care Medicine, with seven beds, headed by Dr. Chen Dechang, known as "the father of critical care medicine in China. ".

In 1989, the former Ministry of Health formally requested all tertiary general hospitals to set up ICU, the construction of the National Department of Critical Care Medicine. In 2009, the former Ministry of Health officially announced the addition of "critical care medicine" to the list of subjects in medical institutions, and issued "guidelines for the construction and management of critical care medicine (for Trial Implementation) " (hereinafter referred to as "guidelines") . The guideline requires that at least one ICU should be set up in general hospitals of Grade II and above, and the number of beds of critical care medicine in general hospitals of Grade III should account for 2% ~ 8% of the total number of hospital beds.

At the beginning of his term of office, Liu Xiaojun was determined to change the state of "half-dead" in the ICU of the Second Affiliated Hospital of Zheng University. He put down the provincial Three-a hospital director of the body, a weekend to the provincial counties and cities to see the same. In his "promotion" , when the primary hospital ICU doctors need to consult higher hospital doctors, often the first thought is that they know the province's expert Liu Xiaojun.

Today, the Second Affiliated Hospital of Zhengzhou University ICU has 7 ambulances, a month from the grass-roots transfer of nearly 200 patients, a single ward of the country's largest number of external ICU patients. With patients, the ICU ward of the hospital has also begun a biennial expansion pace, from 8 beds to 13,20 beds, and sometimes additional temporary beds. In 2014, the ICU moved to the new ward as a whole, opening 40 beds.

Behind the expansion of intensive care unit (ICU) in the Second Affiliated Hospital of Zhengzhou University is the great development of the Department of Critical Care Medicine in China. Intensive Care Unit (ICU) has become an important index of hospital grading since the beginning of the expansion of public hospitals in China in 2003. "In recent years, the development of ICU in most parts of China has been very fast, definitely exceeding the average rate of hospital development, " said Du Bin, Director of ICU at the Peking Union Medical College Hospital and President of the Chinese Medical Doctors Association's branch of Critical Care Medicine

The initial 12 beds in the ICU have grown to nearly 30 beds in her original The First Hospital of Jiaxing Ward, which is still far from adequate, the chief doctor of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Zhejiang International Hospital in TÃ¢n An told China news weekly, it was later added as a respiratory ICU. She said, "every city-level hospital and even the top hospitals have followed the same path: first increasing the number of beds in the General Icu, then setting up specialist ICU. Many hospitals have moved to new sites and set up larger ICU units. "

"ICU should be the largest department in a general hospital or a large hospital in the future, " said Zhan Qingyuan, director of the Department of respiratory and critical care medicine at sino-japanese Friendship Hospital, "In the future, after carrying out grading diagnosis and treatment completely, what will the big hospitals live on? One is difficult and miscellaneous diseases, one is serious diseases, and then there are major operations. "

Liu Xiaojun also pointed out that, "after the implementation of county-level comprehensive medical reform, the state requires that serious diseases should not leave the county. Now many rural areas of the transfer rate of only 5% , then, provincial hospitals or large hospitals in the general ward, where the patients? Against this backdrop, all departments are likely to have fewer beds in the future, with the exception of the ICU, which will have more."

Despite the rapid expansion of the ICU, it is rare to see a hospital with such a weapon in the ICU where beds and staff are not tight and patients'needs are not met.

As director of the Capital University of Medical Sciences, Xi is one of China's pioneers in the field of critical care medicine. He believes that from the current situation, China's per capita occupancy of ICU beds, compared with the Western developed countries is clearly not enough, domestic ICU is still far from the point of balance between supply and demand. The number of ICU beds per 100,000 people in Germany and Canada is as high as 24.6 and 13.5, respectively, according to the World Federation of Critical Care and critical care medicine.

In 2016, according to the results of the National Icu Census published in the Chinese Journal of Critical Care Medicine by some members of the Chinese Medical Association, the average number of ICU beds per 100,000 population in China was 3.19 in 2014. However, Du explained that the survey did not include specialist ICU and that the number of beds in the general and specialist ICU was roughly the same, meaning that this number could double, but even so, the gap with Germany and Canada is still wide.

"China's population and aging trends from 2015 to 2100, " according to Zhai Zhenwu, a professor at the Center for Population and Development Studies at Renmin University of China and the Beijing Academy of Social Construction, and his team, the proportion of the Chinese population aged 60 and over will top 20 percent around 2024, and the proportion of those aged 65 and over will top 15 percent around 2027. By the first half of this century, China's elderly population will enter a blowout period.

"In ICU, 70 years old is young, 80 years old is middle-aged, and 90 years old is old, " said Zhan. For ICU, especially the medical ICU, the challenge of aging is obvious. "older people are more likely to develop severe illness, and these patients are often difficult to treat, and the population is very large, so ICU resources will certainly not be sufficient in the future. "

According to the guidelines of the former Ministry of Health, the occupancy rate of ICU beds should be 75% , but China news weekly visited the ICU of many hospitals and found that from provincial hospitals to municipal hospitals to county hospitals, from the Central Plain province of Henan to the coastal province of Zhejiang, bed addition is common during peak ICU seasons. The doctors in the ICU have a good reason: patients are so critical that refusing to accept them would endanger their lives. Who is responsible?

Another reason not mentioned is that, due to the low financial investment in public hospitals, hospitals are reluctant to lose patients, especially the high-cost critically ill patients who need to be admitted to the ICU, even though they have exceeded the approved beds under economic pressure.

In the ICU, the nurse performed CPR on the patient. Figure / IC

The "clincher" dilemma

In the intensive care unit of the sino-japanese Friendship Hospital, a 91-year-old man has been living in the same position and treatment for more than four years. Places in the ICU that patients find intolerable, such as constant monitor alarms, lights that never go off at night or day, and extremely limited room for movement because of all kinds of care tubes, etc. , it didn't bother him, he was barely conscious because of the central nervous system disease.

This is not an isolated case. While hundreds of thousands of dollars in ICU costs keep many economically limited families at bay, some patients who benefit little from ICU but have sufficient financial resources to support them have long occupied scarce resources. They often rely on life support techniques such as breathing machines for months or years at a time, and in some patients there is irreversible damage to the body that is otherwise central nervous system, such as cerebral hemorrhage, cerebral infarction caused by Hemiplegia or even long-term coma. These patients tend to be the majority of the ICU "press" population. "almost all of the I.C.U.'s have admitted patients with these conditions, " Du said.

What kind of person is best suited to the ICU? According to the former Ministry of Health guidelines, patients admitted to the intensive-care unit fall into the following four categories: acute, reversible, and already life threatening organ or system failure, patients who may recover in a short period of time after intensive care and intensive treatment; patients with high risk factors and potential life-threatening conditions who may reduce the risk of death after intensive care and effective treatment; On the basis of chronic organ or system dysfunction, acute exacerbation and life-threatening, patients who may return to their original or near-original state after intensive care and treatment and other patients who are suitable for intensive care and treatment in the ICU.

The guidelines also note that end-state, irreversible disease and patients who do not benefit from enhanced surveillance and treatment of chronic wasting diseases and tumors are generally not included in the intensive care unit.

Xi Xiuming wrote that the key to deciding whether a patient should be transferred to the ICU lies in whether it is beneficial to his disease. Patients who are in good condition and do not need to be monitored, or who have no hope of recovery and improved quality of life, do not need to be admitted to the ICU.

Many ICU doctors believe that the most effective treatment in the ICU is usually reversible cases of severe acute illness, such as multiple traumatic diseases caused by accidents such as car accidents, which are transferred to the ICU for intensive care and treatment after major surgery, it is possible for the patient to recover after he stabilizes.

But how to define "benefit" is also an ethical question. When the family is adamant that no effort be spared to maintain it, the medical guide can not beat the social conventions. In a sense, Xi argues, these patients also benefit in the ICU -- as if they were dying as soon as they got out, but the question is, how do you think of this kind of living without quality? Do these patients have to stay in the ICU for extended periods of time to receive intensive care?

Zhan Qingyuan thinks, ICU should not admit this kind of patient. A dignified death may have to be considered when there are elderly patients with multiple complications of their own and ICU life support does not result in any improvement in quality of life.

According to a survey conducted by Li Jie and others at Chaoyang Hospital affiliated to Peking University Health Science Center in late 2012,26% of patients stayed in ICU for more than 21 days, the longest cases are more than five years old. The patients ranged in age from 59 to 91. The most common reason why they can not be transferred is the lack of institutions with professional care.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Day and night, the miracle of life in the ICU may be happening all the time. Image / visual China

Xi's 24-bed Intensive Care Unit at the Fuxing Hospital has more than half of the beds in the chronic critical care unit, and six of the patients have been hospitalized for more than a year. Chronic critical illness generally refers to stay in the ICU for more than 7 days, mainly rely on breathing and other life support technology in critically ill patients.

Long-term stay in ICU, first of all, means a large consumption of medical resources, a hospital bed costs about one hundred thousand resources a year, and when ICU beds are tight, this kind of patients caused by the irrational use of resources contradictions is even more obvious.

Their condition is in an awkward Middle Zone, as if it didn't require intensive treatment in the intensive care unit, but there was no breathing apparatus, nutritional support or other high-tech equipment to keep them alive in the general ward of the "Four-wall family" , the number and skills of the medical staff in the general wards are also far from sufficient to take care of the critically ill. Experts say it reflects a structural flaw in China's health system -- a failure to distinguish between acute and chronic diseases.

At the 2019 two sessions of the NPC, Ma Xiaowei, director of the National Health Commission, pointed out that China's medical services are dominated by acute diseases, and the development of medical services in the convalescence and convalescence periods is slow and even short. Therefore, many patients with chronic diseases, such as cancer chemotherapy patients, stroke (commonly known as "stroke") patients, are dependent on the city's third-tier hospitals. As the population ageing accelerates, the demand for chronic care services will undoubtedly multiply, he said, and the urgent need to separate the acute from the chronic is imminent.

For ICU, the treatment value of ICU for critically ill patients can be better displayed by distinguishing chronic severe cases from acute severe cases and using ICU for acute severe cases. Xi Xiuming explained that rehabilitation exercises, nutrition and nursing were the main life support treatment for the patients with chronic severe illness, while the treatment for the patients with acute severe illness included shock rescue, various operations and intensive instrument monitoring.

In Europe and America, Ltach or Nursing Home is the main reception place for the patients with chronic severe illness. On the one hand, this division has eliminated the use of medical resources for patients with acute and severe illness due to long-term stay in the ICU; on the other hand, the number of doctors in such medical institutions is very small, mostly nurses, so the costs are relatively low, help reduce the burden of medical insurance.

Some hospitals in China are trying to set up transitional wards to alleviate the problem of transfer of patients with pressure bed. In 2013, Peking University International Hospital and Xuanwu Hospital Neurosurgery Experts Ling Feng set up a rehabilitation center, Xi Xiuming participated in the construction of ICU. The idea, he says, was to develop more than two dozen ICU beds into "off-line centers" similar to those in Europe, turning patients in hospitals who had long relied on mechanical ventilation to help them recover and get out of the machines, and then it was abandoned because there were no patients.

In this regard, Xi Xiuming pointed out that the policy of medical reimbursement has not been matched, what kind of chronic diseases are included in the treatment of unclear standards, low degree of social acceptance, is the main obstacle to the development of China's LTACH wards.

Zhan Qingyuan's china-japan Friendship Hospital has cooperated with a community hospital to solve the problem of prolonged occupation of ICU resources by pressed bed patients who can not be evacuated from suction machines for a long time, a 22-bed HDU (High Dependency Unit) is expected to be operational within the next month, and barriers to health insurance reimbursement will be removed.

HDU from the United Kingdom, between the ICU and the general ward of the buffer zone, long-term dependence on suction machines, the need to turn over regularly sputum suction, the choice of active life-sustaining patients with advanced cancer is the main HDU admission target. Not only does HDU require less equipment and manpower than the ICU, so it doesn't take up valuable medical resources for critical patients in the ICU, but some HDU practices have shown that patients can get better rehabilitation training here, and reduce complications.

The talent pool

In fact, the ICU is also sub-off season. In the winter of high incidence of influenza is often hard to get a bed, to warm weather in the spring and summer season, it is relatively leisure. In the off-season, Liu's ICU department did not have a patient for two weeks. But at its peak, they treated more than 70 patients at a time. In order to deal with so many patients, had to let all rest of the medical staff to work overtime, the hospital also transferred from other sections of more than 30 nurses. Some people come down from the same class with swollen feet.

According to the guidelines of the former Ministry of Health, the ratio of beds to ICU doctors should be above 1:0.8, and the ratio of beds to nurses should be above 1:3. But Du and others pointed out in 2010 that the average ratio of nurses per bed in mainland China is between 1.37 and 2.02. Many experts admit that with the current extremely low charge for care and the huge manpower cost of ICU, the standards specified in the guide are out of reach, and the ICU with better staffing can only achieve 1:2.5 at the most. At the china-japan Friendship Hospital, for example, the ratio was 1:2.2. As for the requirement of 0.8 doctors per bed, it is impossible to talk about.

The number of nurses in ICU is very high in foreign countries. In Britain, for example, there are at least 7 nurses in one bed. For critically ill patients in the Minute to Win It, the number of health care workers is directly related to the patient's prognosis, and the higher the staffing, the more intensive the care and treatment, experts said.

Under the condition of inadequate ICU staff, patients are inevitably put into potential danger, and the security, order and environment of the ward are faced with challenges.

Du Bin questioned the reasons for adding beds, "Is it true that a hospital has to take on an excess of patients? In some hospitals, the ICU is full, while in other hospitals, the ICU is not full at all. Why don't patients want to go to those hospitals? That's what health policy makers should be thinking about."

Since 2009, the deepening of medical reform, to solve the problem of difficult to see a doctor, grading diagnosis and treatment as a key issue has been frequently mentioned. However, the "Siphon effect" is still obvious, people and property are still excessively concentrated in a few large hospitals. In Taiqian County, the most remote part of Henan Province, for example, he went for technical help and found no patients in the ICU of a local hospital. "because when a patient comes in, the doctor has to say, 'this is a serious case, I've never seen it before, I don't know what to do. ' What will the family do? "

Liu Guoen, a professor of economics at the National Development Research Institute at Peking University, said the main reason residents do not visit primary care facilities is worries about doctors'professional skills, or the quality of medical care. "At the very least, providing the right care should be the bottom line at all levels of health care. The professional knowledge and clinical skills of health technicians are the foundation, but the current situation is still worrying,"said a research report submitted by the Finance and Economic Commission of the National People's Congress in late 2018, insufficient supply and uneven allocation of qualified medical personnel are the main obstacles to the slow development of grading diagnosis and treatment.

In Henan Province, many county-level hospitals set up ICU wards in order to create second-level hospitals. But Liu Xiaojun pointed out that the current situation is that one-third of the county-level hospitals to carry out serious medicine capacity is insufficient, mainly because there is no talent, lack of doctors, lack of nurses. DANCHENG County Chinese Medicine Hospital sets up a second-level hospital this year to provide critical care services. The 11-bed ICU unit currently has only four doctors, three of whom have either a college degree or a working bachelor's degree. From their medical experience, they had worked in neurology or emergency medicine, have no major medical background. "In addition to the county people's Hospital, the county second hospital, the county women's Health Care Hospital and the County Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine are having a tough time these days

Many ICU practitioners believe that the gap in medical hardware resources between different levels of hospitals has gradually narrowed. Hu Mahong, director of ICU at Litongde Hospital in Zhejiang Province, told China Newsweek that even county-level hospitals in Zhejiang can afford the artificial membrane lung (ECMO) , which is considered the most advanced life-support equipment at present, the talent gap remains wide. Du pointed out that nowadays, critical care medicine has developed into an independent medical specialty, whose theoretical system, professional knowledge and skills can not be covered by traditional disciplines, and need to be mastered through systematic theoretical study and clinical practice.

The standardization or homogeneity of clinical treatment is recognized as an important sign of the maturity of medical science. Faced with a case of acute myocardial infarction, it is reasonable to say that the treatment should be the same whether in Beijing or Guangxi. "But the reality is that there are too many differences between hospitals, " Du said. "The differences are definitely not in the technical equipment, but in the concept of treatment and the knowledge and skills acquired. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the ICU ward, the medical staff blows the glove into the balloon shape, writes some encouraging words, refuels for the patient to encourage, has added some vitality to the ward. Image / visual China

"Heterogeneity is the biggest problem in the training of medical professionals in China. " According to Zhan, facing the same disease, even if trained in different hospitals, after training, doctors should agree in principle on how to deal with the disease. But the current situation is, a doctor can get what kind of training, to a large extent depends on the department head of the training program and ideas. Xi Xiuming also believes that the key to developing a good young doctor lies in Continuing education after graduation, the most important of which is the ability to synthesize all kinds of information about the patient and make treatment decisions, china's standardized training system in this area is just beginning.

Unlike foreign countries, where there is a high threshold for medical education and training, the level of Medical Education in China is uneven. In order to alleviate the "supporting" condition in the ICU of some hospitals and the "starving" condition in the ICU of other hospitals, it is more and more important to make up the level of diagnosis and treatment of doctors in different hospitals and the homogenization training of medical students after graduation.

When discussing the problems and challenges of Critical Care Medicine in China, Du bin pointed out that the increase of ICU beds does not mean the corresponding improvement of medical quality, but the personnel engaged in critical care medicine is the most crucial determinant. With the rapid development of ICU in China, it is an indisputable fact that the practitioners lack the necessary training. If it can not be solved in time, it will become a major obstacle to the further development of critical care medicine.

After the second round of health care reform brought the rural population into the new rural cooperative medical care system, many seriously ill patients who gave up treatment in the past can now afford better medical care. That means they don't have to give up the chance to save a life because they don't have the money, Xi said. His best hope is that the future deployment of medical staff will be able to keep up with the development needs of ICU, and some of the ICU will be managed in an open manner, allowing families and nurses to work together to provide more care to critically ill patients, no longer will sedation and various restraints be used to "manage" patients in the ICU who are struggling with life and death. In this way, humanistic care can be fully embodied in clinical treatment as in the most critical stage of the war ââ Intensive Care Unit.
